      'The gods seek Osiris\'s verdict, who threatens to send messengers from the Duat if justice is denied.',
      'Horus is crowned king of Egypt, while Set is elevated to the sky to accompany Ra.',
    ],
    impact: '''Kemenangan Horus memulihkan garis takhta yang sah dan menetapkan model kekuasaan Mesir kuno: setiap firaun yang hidup adalah Horus, setiap firaun yang wafat menjadi Osiris. Set, meski kalah, tidak dilenyapkan, melainkan diberi peran baru sebagai pelindung Ra melawan Apep di langit malam, menunjukkan bahwa kekuatan kekacauan tetap dibutuhkan dalam keseimbangan kosmis. Persidangan delapan puluh tahun ini juga menjadi preseden mitologis bagi konsep hukum dan keadilan ilahi yang menaungi seluruh peradaban Mesir.''',
    impactEn: '''Horus's victory restored the rightful royal line and established the model of ancient Egyptian kingship: every living pharaoh is Horus, every deceased pharaoh becomes Osiris. Set, though defeated, was not destroyed but given a new role as Ra's protector against Apep in the night sky, showing that the power of chaos remained necessary within the cosmic balance. This eighty-year trial also became a mythological precedent for the concept of divine law and justice underpinning all of Egyptian civilization.''',
    meaning: '''Kisah ini melambangkan pertarungan abadi antara tatanan (Ma'at) dan kekacauan (isfet), serta kemenangan hak yang sah atas perebutan paksa. Horus, meski lebih muda dan lemah secara fisik, menang melalui kesabaran, dukungan ibunya, dan keadilan ilahi, bukan semata kekuatan. Mitos ini menjadi dasar legitimasi politik para firaun, mengukuhkan bahwa kekuasaan sejati harus diperoleh melalui hukum dan restu para dewa, bukan kekerasan semata, sekaligus mengajarkan bahwa bahkan kekuatan destruktif seperti Set memiliki tempat yang perlu dalam menjaga keseimbangan dunia.''',
    meaningEn: '''This story symbolizes the eternal struggle between order (Ma'at) and chaos (isfet), and the triumph of rightful claim over forceful usurpation. Horus, though younger and physically weaker, wins through patience, his mother's support, and divine justice, rather than strength alone. The myth became the foundation of pharaonic political legitimacy, affirming that true power must be gained through law and the gods' blessing rather than violence alone, while also teaching that even a destructive force like Set has a necessary place in maintaining the world's balance.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'egypt-ra-apep',
    mythology: 'Egyptian',
    icon: '🐍',
    imageUrl: 'assets/images/Egypt/History/raapep.webp',
    title: 'Ra Melawan Apep',
    titleEn: 'Ra Battles Apep',
    summary: 'Setiap malam, dewa matahari Ra berlayar melintasi dunia bawah yang gelap di dalam kapal suryanya, bertarung melawan ular raksasa kekacauan, Apep, agar matahari dapat terbit kembali esok hari.',
    summaryEn: 'Every night, the sun god Ra sails his solar barque through the dark underworld, battling the giant serpent of chaos, Apep, so that the sun may rise again the next day.',
    timeline: 'Zaman Mitos · Siklus Abadi Matahari',
    timelineEn: 'Mythic Age · The Eternal Cycle of the Sun',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Latar Belakang',
        headingEn: 'Background',
        body: '''Bagi orang Mesir kuno, matahari bukan sekadar benda langit, melainkan wujud dewa Ra yang berlayar melintasi langit siang hari di atas kapal suci bernama Mandjet. Namun setiap senja, ketika matahari tenggelam di ufuk barat, Ra memasuki Duat, dunia bawah yang gelap dan penuh bahaya, dengan menumpang kapal malam bernama Mesektet. Perjalanan melintasi dua belas wilayah Duat ini, yang masing-masing mewakili satu jam malam, digambarkan secara rinci dalam teks-teks pemakaman seperti Kitab Amduat dan Kitab Gerbang. Ra tidak berlayar sendirian; ia ditemani rombongan dewa pelindung, termasuk Set yang berdiri di haluan kapal dengan tombaknya, karena satu ancaman purba selalu menanti di kegelapan: Apep, ular raksasa kekacauan yang telah ada sejak sebelum penciptaan dan bertekad menelan matahari untuk mengembalikan dunia ke kekosongan primordial.''',
        bodyEn: '''For the ancient Egyptians, the sun was not merely a celestial object but the very form of the god Ra, who sailed across the daytime sky aboard his sacred barque, the Mandjet. Yet every evening, as the sun set on the western horizon, Ra entered the Duat, the dark and perilous underworld, aboard his night barque, the Mesektet. This journey through the twelve regions of the Duat, each representing one hour of the night, is described in detail in funerary texts such as the Book of Amduat and the Book of Gates. Ra did not sail alone; he was accompanied by a retinue of protective gods, including Set, who stood at the prow with his spear, for one primordial threat always awaited in the darkness: Apep, the giant serpent of chaos who had existed since before creation and was determined to swallow the sun to return the world to primordial emptiness.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Wujud dan Ancaman Apep',
        headingEn: 'The Form and Threat of Apep',
        body: '''Apep digambarkan sebagai ular raksasa yang panjangnya mencapai puluhan meter, bersisik batu akik keras, dengan raungan yang mampu menggetarkan seluruh Duat. Ia tidak diciptakan oleh para dewa dan tidak tunduk pada tatanan mereka; sebagian teks bahkan menyebutnya lahir dari tali pusar Ra sendiri saat penciptaan atau dari lumpur purba sebelum dunia terbentuk, menjadikannya representasi murni dari isfet, kekacauan yang berlawanan total dengan Ma'at. Setiap malam, Apep menunggu di titik-titik tergelap perjalanan Ra, kadang berusaha meminum seluruh air sungai Duat agar kapal surya kandas, kadang menyerang langsung dengan hendak menelan Ra bulat-bulat. Jika Apep berhasil, matahari tidak akan terbit, dan dunia akan terjerumus dalam kegelapan abadi serta kembali pada kekacauan sebelum penciptaan, sehingga pertempuran ini bukan sekadar duel pribadi melainkan pertaruhan eksistensi seluruh kosmos.''',
        bodyEn: '''Apep is depicted as a giant serpent stretching dozens of meters long, scaled with hard flint, whose roar could shake the entire Duat. He was not created by the gods and did not submit to their order; some texts even claim he was born from Ra's own umbilical cord at creation, or from the primordial mud before the world took shape, making him a pure representation of isfet, the chaos utterly opposed to Ma'at. Every night, Apep waited at the darkest points of Ra's journey, sometimes attempting to drink up the entire river of the Duat so the solar barque would run aground, sometimes attacking outright to swallow Ra whole. If Apep succeeded, the sun would not rise, and the world would plunge into eternal darkness and revert to the chaos before creation, making this battle not merely a personal duel but a wager on the existence of the entire cosmos.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Pertempuran di Kegelapan Duat',
        headingEn: 'Battle in the Darkness of the Duat',
        body: '''Ketika Apep menyerang, seluruh awak kapal surya bersiaga. Set, dengan kekuatan dan keberaniannya yang legendaris, berdiri di haluan Mesektet dan menikam Apep berulang kali dengan tombak besi meteoritnya, sementara para dewa lain seperti Isis dan Neith melafalkan mantra-mantra sihir kuno untuk melumpuhkan sang ular. Dewi Bastet, dalam wujud kucing, kadang digambarkan memenggal kepala Apep dengan pisau, sebuah adegan populer yang dilukiskan di makam-makam kerajaan Lembah Para Raja. Meski ditikam, dipotong, dan dibakar berulang kali, Apep tidak pernah benar-benar mati; ia selalu pulih dan kembali menyerang malam berikutnya, karena ia mewakili kekacauan abadi yang mustahil dimusnahkan selamanya, hanya dapat ditahan dan dikalahkan sementara melalui perjuangan tanpa henti.''',
        bodyEn: '''When Apep struck, the entire crew of the solar barque sprang to action. Set, with his legendary strength and courage, stood at the prow of the Mesektet and repeatedly stabbed Apep with his meteoric iron spear, while other gods such as Isis and Neith chanted ancient magical spells to paralyze the serpent. The goddess Bastet, in cat form, was sometimes depicted beheading Apep with a knife, a popular scene painted in the royal tombs of the Valley of the Kings. Though stabbed, cut, and burned repeatedly, Apep never truly died; he always recovered and returned to attack the following night, for he represented an eternal chaos that could never be permanently destroyed, only restrained and defeated anew through unending struggle.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Peran Manusia dalam Pertempuran Kosmis',
        headingEn: 'Humanity\'s Role in the Cosmic Battle',
        body: '''Orang Mesir kuno percaya bahwa mereka bukan sekadar penonton pasif dalam pertarungan kosmis ini, melainkan turut berperan menjaga tatanan dunia. Para pendeta di kuil-kuil besar seperti di Karnak melakukan ritual harian yang disebut Kitab Menumbangkan Apep (Book of Overthrowing Apep), yakni membuat patung lilin atau papirus bergambar ular Apep, lalu meludahinya, menginjaknya, menikamnya dengan pisau, dan akhirnya membakarnya sambil melafalkan mantra kutukan. Ritual ini dipercaya secara magis membantu Ra dalam pertempurannya di Duat, memastikan matahari benar-benar terbit esok pagi. Gerhana matahari dan badai gurun yang tiba-tiba dianggap sebagai tanda bahwa Apep untuk sesaat berhasil mengganggu perjalanan Ra, memicu kepanikan dan ritual darurat di seluruh negeri hingga cahaya matahari kembali normal.''',
        bodyEn: '''The ancient Egyptians believed they were not merely passive spectators of this cosmic battle but played an active role in preserving world order. Priests in great temples such as Karnak performed a daily ritual called the Book of Overthrowing Apep, making wax or papyrus figurines of the serpent, then spitting on them, trampling them, stabbing them with knives, and finally burning them while reciting curses. This ritual was believed to magically assist Ra in his battle within the Duat, ensuring the sun would truly rise the following morning. Solar eclipses and sudden desert storms were regarded as signs that Apep had momentarily succeeded in disrupting Ra's journey, triggering panic and emergency rituals across the land until the sunlight returned to normal.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Penutup',
        headingEn: 'Closing',
        body: '''Setiap fajar, ketika kapal surya Mandjet muncul kembali di cakrawala timur, kemenangan Ra atas Apep dirayakan sebagai bukti bahwa tatanan (Ma'at) sekali lagi berhasil menaklukkan kekacauan (isfet), meski hanya untuk sehari. Siklus ini akan terus berulang selamanya, malam demi malam, karena Apep tidak pernah benar-benar terkalahkan secara permanen, ia hanya ditunda. Bagi orang Mesir kuno, mitos ini menjelaskan fenomena alam seperti terbit dan tenggelamnya matahari, gerhana, serta badai, sekaligus menegaskan bahwa keteraturan alam semesta bukanlah sesuatu yang otomatis atau terjamin, melainkan hasil perjuangan tanpa henti yang melibatkan para dewa dan, melalui ritual, manusia itu sendiri.''',
        bodyEn: '''Every dawn, when the solar barque Mandjet reappeared on the eastern horizon, Ra's victory over Apep was celebrated as proof that order (Ma'at) had once again triumphed over chaos (isfet), if only for a day. This cycle would repeat forever, night after night, for Apep was never truly defeated permanently, only held at bay. For the ancient Egyptians, this myth explained natural phenomena such as sunrise and sunset, eclipses, and storms, while affirming that the order of the universe was not something automatic or guaranteed, but the result of a ceaseless struggle involving the gods and, through ritual, humanity itself.''',
      ),
    ],
